BT /F1 10.50 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 711.80 Tm (This 'password leak' example is visceral - pause on it. Ask the room: 'would you want your password in) Tj ET
BT /F1 10.50 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 697.40 Tm (the API response?' That makes the need for a DTO obvious and memorable, rather than abstract.) Tj ET
0.160 0.660 0.250 rg 58.00 683.00 3.00 50.80 re f
BT /F2 15.00 Tf 0.100 0.100 0.120 rg 1 0 0 1 58.00 664.00 Tm (Slide 5 - What is a DTO?) Tj ET
0.040 0.520 1.000 rg 58.00 647.00 496.00 1.40 re f
BT /F2 9.50 Tf 0.420 0.420 0.460 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 631.00 Tm (ON SCREEN) Tj ET
BT /F1 10.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 615.00 Tm (A definition and three reason cards: security, flexibility, decoupling.) Tj ET
0.720 0.720 0.760 rg 58.00 601.50 3.00 35.50 re f
BT /F2 9.50 Tf 0.040 0.340 0.780 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 590.50 Tm (SAY \(read this aloud\)) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 574.50 Tm (So, what is a DTO? It stands for Data Transfer Object, and it is exactly what the name says - a) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 559.30 Tm (plain, simple Java class whose only job is to carry data between your app and the outside world. It) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 544.10 Tm (has no database annotations and no logic. It carries only what the caller actually needs. Let me) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 528.90 Tm (give you the three reasons we use one, shown as the three cards.) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 508.70 Tm (First, security. You hide sensitive fields. The password lives on the entity, but it is simply not on the) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 493.50 Tm (DTO, so it can never slip out. We just saw that.) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 473.30 Tm (Second, flexibility. You shape the response to fit the caller. Maybe one screen needs a short) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 458.10 Tm (summary and another needs full detail - you can have different DTOs for each, from the same) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 442.90 Tm (entity. You are not stuck sending every field every time.) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 422.70 Tm (Third, decoupling - a fancy word for 'keeping things independent'. Your database can change) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 407.50 Tm (without breaking your public API. Rename a column, split a table - you just adjust the mapping) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 392.30 Tm (inside, and the callers outside never even notice.) Tj ET
0.040 0.520 1.000 rg 58.00 377.10 3.00 219.40 re f
BT /F2 9.50 Tf 0.100 0.550 0.200 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 366.10 Tm (EMPHASISE) Tj ET
BT /F1 10.50 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 350.10 Tm (Give them the one-liner to memorise: 'The entity maps to the database. The DTO travels over the wire.') Tj ET
BT /F1 10.50 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 335.70 Tm (They often look almost identical, but they exist for completely different reasons - and keeping them) Tj ET
BT /F1 10.50 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 321.30 Tm (separate is what lets an API grow safely over years.) Tj ET
0.160 0.660 0.250 rg 58.00 306.90 3.00 65.20 re f
