BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 448.10 Tm (Step one - create your own exception class. It extends RuntimeException, and it takes a message) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 432.90 Tm (in its constructor. So we make a class called ResourceNotFoundException, and we can give it any) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 417.70 Tm (message we like, such as 'Post not found with id five'.) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 397.50 Tm (Step two - and this is the clever bit - we put an annotation on that class: at-ResponseStatus, with) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 382.30 Tm (NOT FOUND. This single line tells Spring, 'whenever this exception is thrown and nobody catches) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 367.10 Tm (it, automatically set the response code to 404'. No try-catch needed anywhere. The annotation) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 351.90 Tm (does the wiring for you.) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 331.70 Tm (Step three - we throw it, at the moment we discover the item is missing, using a neat method) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 316.50 Tm (called orElseThrow, which we will see on the next slide.) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 296.30 Tm (Look at the code. The exception class itself is tiny - just the annotation and a constructor that) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 281.10 Tm (passes the message up. That is it. Three steps - create, annotate, throw - and ugly 500s become) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 265.90 Tm (clean 404s.) Tj ET
