BT /F2 15.00 Tf 0.100 0.100 0.120 rg 1 0 0 1 58.00 746.00 Tm (Slide 16 - Horizontal vs vertical scaling) Tj ET
0.040 0.520 1.000 rg 58.00 729.00 496.00 1.40 re f
BT /F2 9.50 Tf 0.420 0.420 0.460 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 713.00 Tm (ON SCREEN) Tj ET
BT /F1 10.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 697.00 Tm (Two columns - vertical scaling \(one bigger server\) versus horizontal scaling \(more servers behind a load) Tj ET
BT /F1 10.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 683.50 Tm (balancer\).) Tj ET
0.720 0.720 0.760 rg 58.00 670.00 3.00 49.00 re f
BT /F2 9.50 Tf 0.040 0.340 0.780 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 659.00 Tm (SAY \(read this aloud\)) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 643.00 Tm (Let's talk about handling more traffic - what we call scaling. There are two ways to do it, and the) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 627.80 Tm (difference is simple once you picture it.) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 607.60 Tm (The first is vertical scaling - scaling up. This means taking your one machine and making it more) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 592.40 Tm (powerful - more memory, more CPU. It is simple, but it has a ceiling - you cannot keep adding) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 577.20 Tm (power forever, there is a biggest machine you can buy. And big machines get very expensive.) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 562.00 Tm (Plus, it is still just one machine - one point of failure.) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 541.80 Tm (The second is horizontal scaling - scaling out. This means adding more machines, each running a) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 526.60 Tm (copy of the same service, with a traffic director in front of them. There is no real ceiling - just keep) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 511.40 Tm (adding machines. It is cost-effective, because you use many ordinary machines instead of one) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 496.20 Tm (giant one. And it is naturally fault-tolerant - if one machine dies, the others carry on.) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 476.00 Tm (Think of it like a shop checkout. Vertical scaling is training your one cashier to work faster - there is) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 460.80 Tm (a limit. Horizontal scaling is just opening more checkout counters.) Tj ET
0.040 0.520 1.000 rg 58.00 445.60 3.00 219.40 re f
BT /F2 9.50 Tf 0.100 0.550 0.200 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 434.60 Tm (EMPHASISE) Tj ET
BT /F1 10.50 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 418.60 Tm (Connect it forward to set up Session 4: microservices are designed for horizontal scaling. Because) Tj ET
BT /F1 10.50 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 404.20 Tm (each service is small and remembers nothing between requests, you can spin up as many copies as) Tj ET
BT /F1 10.50 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 389.80 Tm (you need and spread traffic across them - which is exactly how the cloud works.) Tj ET
0.160 0.660 0.250 rg 58.00 375.40 3.00 65.20 re f
BT /F2 15.00 Tf 0.100 0.100 0.120 rg 1 0 0 1 58.00 356.40 Tm (Slide 17 - Load balancing & high availability) Tj ET
0.040 0.520 1.000 rg 58.00 339.40 496.00 1.40 re f
BT /F2 9.50 Tf 0.420 0.420 0.460 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 323.40 Tm (ON SCREEN) Tj ET
BT /F1 10.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 307.40 Tm (A load-balancer diagram: clients to a load balancer to three instances of a service.) Tj ET
0.720 0.720 0.760 rg 58.00 293.90 3.00 35.50 re f
BT /F2 9.50 Tf 0.040 0.340 0.780 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 282.90 Tm (SAY \(read this aloud\)) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 266.90 Tm (So if you have three copies of a service running, a natural question pops up - which copy does) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 251.70 Tm (each request go to? That is the job of a load balancer. It sits in front of your copies and spreads) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 236.50 Tm (the incoming traffic evenly across them. Think of it as the person at the front of a bank who directs) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 221.30 Tm (you to whichever teller is free.) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 201.10 Tm (This gives us two big wins. First, load balancing itself - no single copy gets overwhelmed, because) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 185.90 Tm (the work is shared. And second, high availability - this is the important one. If one copy crashes,) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 170.70 Tm (the load balancer simply notices and stops sending traffic to it. The other copies keep serving, and) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 155.50 Tm (your users never even notice there was a problem. The system stays up.) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 135.30 Tm (In the Spring world, this is handled by tools in Spring Cloud - things with names like Eureka and an) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 120.10 Tm (API Gateway. Don't worry about those names yet - they are exactly what we build, hands-on, in) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 104.90 Tm (Session 4. For now, just hold the picture: a traffic director sharing work across copies, keeping) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 89.70 Tm (everything running smoothly.) Tj ET
